  <!-- Practical Guidance -->
  <h2 id="practical-guidance" class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold font-heading text-navy mb-4">Practical Guidance: How Much RCF Do You Need?</h2>
  <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-6 shadow-sm mb-6">
    <ul class="space-y-3 text-text-light">
      <li><strong class="text-navy">Light fuel oil (diesel, MDO):</strong> 3,000&ndash;5,000 &times;g is generally sufficient for water and particulate removal.</li>
      <li><strong class="text-navy">Heavy fuel oil (HFO, bunker):</strong> 6,000&ndash;9,000 &times;g recommended due to high viscosity and small density differential between oil and water.</li>
      <li><strong class="text-navy">Lube oil and gear oil:</strong> 5,000&ndash;8,000 &times;g depending on contamination level and particle size.</li>
      <li><strong class="text-navy">Beverage clarification (beer, wine):</strong> 6,000&ndash;10,000 &times;g for removal of yeast, protein, and fine solids.</li>
      <li><strong class="text-navy">Pharmaceutical liquids:</strong> 8,000&ndash;12,000+ &times;g for sub-micron particle removal.</li>
      <li><strong class="text-navy">Coolant and metalworking fluid:</strong> 4,000&ndash;7,000 &times;g for tramp oil removal and metal fines separation.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mb-4">These are general ranges. Actual RCF requirements depend on the density differential between phases, viscosity of the continuous phase, and required separation sharpness. Dolphin Centrifuge engineers can calculate the required G-factor for your specific application and recommend the appropriate <a href="/disc-stack-centrifuge/" class="text-navy font-semibold hover:text-gold transition-colors">centrifuge model</a>.</p>

  <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mb-6">Call <a href="tel:+12485222573" class="text-navy font-semibold hover:text-gold transition-colors">(248) 522-2573</a> or email <a href="mailto:sales@dolphincentrifuge.com" class="text-navy font-semibold hover:text-gold transition-colors">sales@dolphincentrifuge.com</a> for application-specific RCF calculations.</p>

  <!-- Summary -->
  <h2 id="summary" class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold font-heading text-navy mb-4">Summary</h2>
  <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mb-4">RCF and RPM are commonly confused and interchanged terms in the centrifuge world. These two terms are significantly different, as explained above.</p>
  <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mb-10">For the end-user, the RCF (aka g-force) is a crucial term because it defines the effectiveness of the centrifuge. The RPM is the bowl speed indicator, but the RPM does not convey any useful information for the application or the process.</p>

  <!-- FAQ -->
  <div id="faq" class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-100 shadow-sm p-6 md:p-8 mt-10 mb-6">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-navy mb-6">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div>
        <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-navy mb-2">What is the difference between RCF and RPM in centrifuge specifications?</h3>
        <p class="text-text-light text-sm">RPM (revolutions per minute) measures rotational speed, while RCF (relative centrifugal force, in × g) measures the centrifugal force at the bowl wall. Two centrifuges running at the same RPM produce very different RCF values depending on bowl diameter — larger bowls generate higher g-force at the same RPM.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-navy mb-2">Why is RCF more important than RPM for comparing centrifuges?</h3>
        <p class="text-text-light text-sm">RCF directly determines separation performance — it governs whether particles of a given size and density will sediment within the available residence time. RPM alone is meaningless without knowing bowl radius. When comparing centrifuges for a separation application, always compare on RCF, not RPM.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-navy mb-2">How is RCF calculated from RPM and bowl radius?</h3>
        <p class="text-text-light text-sm">RCF = 1.118 × 10⁻⁵ × r × N², where r is the bowl radius in centimeters and N is the speed in RPM. This gives the centrifugal force at the bowl wall as a multiple of gravitational acceleration (× g). Dolphin Centrifuge can provide RCF values for specific centrifuge models on request.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

